<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_cryptography" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Classical cryptography">classical cryptography</=
a>, the <b>Hill cipher</b> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Po=
lygraphic_substitution" title=3D"Polygraphic substitution">polygraphic subs=
titution cipher</a> based on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linea=
r_algebra" title=3D"Linear algebra">linear algebra</a>. Invented by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lester_S._Hill" title=3D"Lester S. Hill">=
Lester S. Hill</a> in 1929, it was the first polygraphic cipher in which it=
 was practical (though barely) to operate on more than three symbols at onc=
e.
</p><p>The following discussion assumes an elementary knowledge of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_(mathematics)" title=3D"Matrix (ma=
thematics)">matrices</a>.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Encryption">Encryption</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DHill_cipher&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Encryption"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Each letter is represented by a number <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Modular_arithmetic" title=3D"Modular arithmetic">modulo</a> 26. Tho=
ugh this is not an essential feature of the cipher, this simple scheme is o=
ften used:
</p>
