title=3D"Confusion and diffusion">diffusion</a>, and an <i>n</i>-dimensiona=
l Hill cipher can diffuse fully across <i>n</i> symbols at once.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Decryption">Decryption</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DHill_cipher&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Decryption"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In order to decrypt, we turn the ciphertext back into a vector, then sim=
ply multiply by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_inversi=
on" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Matrix inversion">inverse matrix</a> of =
the key matrix (IFK<span style=3D"color:silver">/</span>VIV<span style=3D"c=
olor:silver">/</span>VMI in letters). We find that, <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_arithmetic" title=3D"Modular arithmetic">modulo</=
a> 26, the inverse of the matrix used in the previous example is:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e {\begin{pmatrix}6&amp;24&amp;1\\13&amp;16&amp;10\\20&amp;17&amp;15\end{pm=
atrix}}^{-1}{\pmod {26}}\equiv {\begin{pmatrix}8&amp;5&amp;10\\21&amp;8&amp=
;21\\21&amp;12&amp;8\end{pmatrix}}}">
