<p>which gets us back to 'ACT', as expected.
</p><p>One complication exists in picking the encrypting matrix:
</p>
<ol><li>Not all matrices have an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I=
nvertible_matrix" title=3D"Invertible matrix">inverse</a>. The matrix will =
have an inverse if and only if its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Determinant" title=3D"Determinant">determinant</a> is inversible modulo n,=
 where n is the modular base.</li></ol>
<p>Thus, if we work modulo 26 as above, the determinant must be nonzero, an=
d must not be divisible by 2 or 13. If the determinant is 0, or has common =
factors with the modular base, then the matrix cannot be used in the Hill c=
ipher, and another matrix must be chosen (otherwise it will not be possible=
 to decrypt). Fortunately, matrices which satisfy the conditions to be used=
 in the Hill cipher are fairly common.
</p><p>For our example key matrix:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e {\begin{vmatrix}6&amp;24&amp;1\\13&amp;16&amp;10\\20&amp;17&amp;15\end{vm=
atrix}}=3D6(16\cdot 15-10\cdot 17)-24(13\cdot 15-10\cdot 20)+1(13\cdot 17-1=
6\cdot 20)=3D441\equiv 25{\pmod {26}}}">
