ine"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"d=
isplay: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=
=3D"{\displaystyle 26=3D2\times 13}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>26</mn>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>2</mn>
        <mo>=C3=97<!-- =C3=97 --></mo>
        <mn>13</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 26=3D2\times =
13}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/e2f52d6521a1f06fcdb154b3371d30321685da25" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:11.751ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 26=
=3D2\times 13}"></span>, 25 has no common factors with 26, and this matrix =
can be used for the Hill cipher.
</p><p>The risk of the determinant having common factors with the modulus c=
an be eliminated by making the modulus <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Prime_number" title=3D"Prime number">prime</a>. Consequently, a useful=
 variant of the Hill cipher adds 3 extra symbols (such as a space, a period=
 and a question mark) to increase the modulus to 29.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Example">Example</h2><span =
