<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Security">Security</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DHill_cipher&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Security"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The basic Hill cipher is vulnerable to a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Known-plaintext_attack" title=3D"Known-plaintext attack">known-pl=
aintext attack</a> because it is completely <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Linear" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Linear">linear</a>. An opp=
onent who intercepts <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inlin=
e"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"dis=
play: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"=
{\displaystyle n^{2}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msup>
          <mi>n</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle n^{2}}</annot=
ation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/ac9810bbdafe4a6a8061338db0f74e25b7952620" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:2.449ex; height:2.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle n^{=
2}}"></span> plaintext/ciphertext character pairs can set up a linear syste=
m which can (usually) be easily solved; if it happens that this system is i=
ndeterminate, it is only necessary to add a few more plaintext/ciphertext p=
airs. Calculating this solution by standard linear algebra algorithms then =
takes very little time.
</p><p>While matrix multiplication alone does not result in a secure cipher=
 it is still a useful step when combined with other <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Non-linear" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Non-linear">no=
n-linear</a> operations, because matrix multiplication can provide <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confusion_and_diffusion" title=3D"Confusi=
on and diffusion">diffusion</a>. For example, an appropriately chosen matri=
x can guarantee that small differences before the matrix multiplication wil=
l result in large differences after the matrix multiplication. Indeed, some=
 modern ciphers use a matrix multiplication step to provide diffusion.  For=
 example, the MixColumns step in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A=
dvanced_Encryption_Standard" title=3D"Advanced Encryption Standard">AES</a>=
 is a matrix multiplication. The function <i>g</i> in <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Twofish" title=3D"Twofish">Twofish</a> is a combination=
 of non-linear S-boxes with a carefully chosen matrix multiplication (MDS).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Key_space_size">Key space s=
ize</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DHill_cip=
her&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Key space siz=
e"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Key_space_(cryptography)" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Key space (cryptography)">key space</a> is th=
e set of all possible keys. The key space size is the number of possible ke=
ys. The effective <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Key_size" title=
=3D"Key size">key size</a>, in number of bits, is the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_logarithm" title=3D"Binary logarithm">binary log=
arithm</a> of the key space size.
</p><p>There are <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><=
span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display=
: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\di=
splaystyle 26^{n^{2}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msup>
          <mn>26</mn>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <msup>
              <mi>n</mi>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>2</mn>
              </mrow>
            </msup>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 26^{n^{2}}}</=
annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/1f51a643ec8b48bc33117bd0149ab4be5f185db0" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:4.375ex; height:3.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 26^=
{n^{2}}}"></span> matrices of dimension <i>n</i> =C3=97 <i>n</i>. Thus <spa=
